    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/https___doi_org_10_21105_joss_08070__task_001/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Spectri Py's compare Spectri Py() and filter Spectri Py() functions allow spectra comparison, and filtering and processing routines, respectively, from the matchms Python library to be called directly from R. These functions internally translate the MS data from a Spectra::Spectra object to the respective Python MS data structures, execute the Python functions, and collect and convert the results to R data types",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes the wrapping mechanism (compareSpectriPy and filterSpectriPy functions) but does not provide an explicit architecture diagram or formal CrossLanguageIntegrationLayer document. The mechanism is described in prose and code examples rather than as a formal architectural specification.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-21105-joss-08070",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Architecture diagram or document describing the CrossLanguageIntegrationLayer showing how Python MS package functions are wrapped into R function interfaces",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:56:21.159820+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/https___doi_org_10_21105_joss_08070__task_001/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "These functions also handle the conversion, and any required renaming and reformatting of spectra metadata, such as MS level, retention times, or any other arbitrary metadata available in the MS data object.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes data marshalling and type conversion at a high level but does not provide a formal technical specification document with detailed conversion rules. The description is embedded in the paper narrative rather than as a standalone specification.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-21105-joss-08070",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Technical specification document detailing the function-wrapping mechanism, data marshalling protocol, and type conversion rules between R and Python",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:56:21.159820+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/https___doi_org_10_21105_joss_08070__task_001/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "As an example, the Cosine (i.e., Dot product) and Cosine Hungarian similarity scores are compared between two sets of spectra, calculated with Spectra's built-in compare Spectra() and Spectri Py's compare Spectri Py() calling the Cosine Hungarian function from matchms, respectively.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper provides example code and a figure comparing results from wrapped Python functions (Cosine Hungarian from matchms) executed in R, but this is not a formal validation report\u2014it is a demonstration example within the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-21105-joss-08070",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Validation report confirming wrapped Python MS functions execute correctly within R Spectra workflows with correct data interchange",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:56:21.159820+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/https___doi_org_10_21105_joss_08070__task_001/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The candidate task card frames the expected outputs as formal deliverables (architecture diagram, technical specification document, validation report) that would be produced as part of a reconstruction or engineering task. However, the paper is a software publication describing an already-implemented tool, not a task specification or project plan. The paper does describe the technical mechanisms but in narrative and code-example form rather than as formal standalone documents.",
        "The research question is well-aligned with the paper's scope, but the expected outputs appear to be aspirational engineering artifacts rather than outputs the paper itself produces. The paper documents the tool's design and functionality but does not present formal architecture diagrams, specification documents, or validation reports as separate deliverables."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 2,
